<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: CHANCES OF RESCUING SEA LION SEEN AS 
IMPROVED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
County animal control officers hope to try in the next few days to rescue 
Gilly, the young California sea lion with a gill net slicing into its neck, a 
Malibu veterinarian said. 
</P>
<P>
"We think the chances are much better this time," said Dr. Nancy Smith, who 
organized a campaign to raise more than $4,400 to buy a net gun that she will 
donate to the county Department of Animal Control. 
</P>
<P>
Smith said the instrument, which costs $3,100, has been ordered and is expected 
to arrive this week. The remainder of the funds will also be donated to the 
county. 
</P>
<P>
Gilly first attracted widespread attention in February when a fisherman spotted 
it on a bait platform a quarter of a mile off the Malibu Pier, where the sea 
lion often rests. Rescuers have tried several times to capture it by throwing a 
net over it, but Gilly has eluded them. Experts have said that unless the 
animal is captured and the net removed, it will eventually choke to death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
