<HEADLINE>
<P>
THIEF STEALS PICKUP, GETS CARGO OF CASH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A thief escaped with $15,000 to $30,000 Wednesday morning when he stole a 
courier service pickup that was parked at a bank. 
</P>
<P>
At 9:07 a.m., William Hanson, a driver for Heritage Courier Services, parked 
the pickup at the Bank of Commerce branch office in the 8900 block of Miramar 
Road to make a deposit for a client, according to San Diego police spokesman 
Dave Cohen. 
</P>
<P>
When Hanson left the bank at 9:12, the truck was gone, Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
A bank employee spotted the truck shortly after noon a block away. The money, 
which had been in a safe fashioned from a tool box, was gone. The safe had been 
opened without force and there were no signs that the pickup's doors or 
ignition had been tampered with. 
</P>
<P>
Cohen said this led police to believe whoever stole the money had a key for the 
truck and knew the safe combination. In addition to the cash, the safe 
contained an undetermined number of checks. 
</P>
<P>
Cohen said a witness saw a young, blond woman wearing light-colored clothing 
open the door of the truck while it was parked in the bank parking lot. Police 
have no suspects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
