<HEADLINE>
<P>
STAFF QUIT, RIVAL PAPER STARTED AS ISLANDER IS SOLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IAN M. ROSE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Down at Lolo Saldana's barber shop, residents of Avalon were abuzz this week 
over news that the city's longtime weekly newspaper, the Catalina Islander, had 
been sold to an out-of-state company. 
</P>
<P>
And not only that, four of the paper's five employees had quit their jobs. And 
one of them is starting up a rival paper. 
</P>
<P>
All this change has come as a surprise to the 2,500 residents of Santa Catalina 
Island, where Donald Haney's family had published the 75-year-old community 
paper since 1955. 
</P>
<P>
"This was a complete shock," said Saldana, who has been cutting hair in Avalon 
for 35 years. 
</P>
<P>
Haney and his wife, Ann, who edited and published the Islander together, 
announced last week that they had sold the paper to Independent News Corp., a 
Rhode Island-based company that owns a number of news weeklies and shoppers 
throughout the country. 
</P>
<P>
"I love the town and the people," Haney said in an interview Wednesday. But, he 
added, "I'm also tired after 35 years." He said the couple had sold the paper 
for health reasons but preferred not to disclose the details. 
</P>
<P>
The Haneys, both in their late 50s, plan to move back to the mainland and look 
for a home near Bakersfield, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, a day after the new owners took over operations, all but one of 
the paper's staff of five quit their jobs after being reprimanded by the 
company's president, Ted Holmberg, for leaving the business unattended during 
lunch hour. 
</P>
<P>
Lenni Hill, who was the Islander's office manager, and other staff members said 
Holmberg had humiliated them. 
</P>
<P>
"(Holmberg) said, " 'You're all stupid. You don't know how to run a business,' 
" Hill recalled. 
</P>
<P>
Mary Burke, who was a typesetter at the Islander before quitting, backed up 
Hill's account. "I've never been treated by an employer like that, and I never 
want to be again," Burke said. 
</P>
<P>
Holmberg, who works out of the company's East Coast offices, could not be 
reached for comment, but the new publisher of the Islander, Lindsay Lewis, said 
she did not recall her boss using the word "stupid." 
</P>
<P>
"We wanted to institute professional, business-like attitudes," Lewis said. 
"They decided that was not the way they wanted to operate and they left." 
</P>
<P>
Over the next few days Hill put together a small group of residents to start up 
a new paper, the Avalon Bay News. 
</P>
<P>
Hill predicted that the new paper will have more community news than the 
Islander. 
</P>
<P>
"They came in from Texas," Hill said of the Islander's new owners, "and they're 
just not our kind of people." 
</P>
<P>
The Islander's new managing editor, Julie Schoeneberg, is from Texas, where the 
company owns several newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
But Lewis said the new owners realize that "we'll have to learn" about the 
island. "We don't make any presumptions that we know all about Catalina." 
</P>
<P>
The first issue of the Avalon Bay News, 24 letter-size pages, is being printed 
at Catalina Printing and is due to hit the streets today. Hill said Chuck Holt, 
the owner of the printing company, is one of four other people who worked 
around the clock this week to put out the inaugural issue. 
</P>
<P>
For the next two weeks, the new paper will be offering yearlong subscriptions 
at $22.50, undercutting the competition by $2.50. 
</P>
<P>
Both Hill and Lewis said they look forward to competition, which they said 
keeps a newspaper healthy. 
</P>
<P>
But whatever the outcome, Haney said, the Islander has changed forever: 
</P>
<P>
"The days of the small newspaper have disappeared along with the small farm." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Publisher Donald Haney, front, with Islander staff members last 
November: back row from left, Teri Plett, Bill Meister, Chris Abel; next row, 
Judy Atchison, Helen Lehr; next row, Mary Burke, Ann Haney. Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
