<HEADLINE>
<P>
CERULLO TO MOVE SAN DIEGO MINISTRY TO EX-PTL 'HERITAGE USA' PARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR., TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Morris Cerullo, the San Diego-based evangelist who is buying the Christian 
theme park Jim Bakker built in Ft. Mill, S.C., said Wednesday that he plans to 
move his entire ministry to the site by the middle of next year, when the park 
is scheduled to reopen. 
</P>
<P>
Cerullo estimated that his operations in San Diego employ 150 full- and 
part-time staffers, but he said plans for relocation had not been discussed 
with them yet. 
</P>
<P>
He said the 2,200-acre "New Heritage USA" site, which Jim Bakker built up as 
the cornerstone of the now defunct PTL Club, "will be a clean, wholesome 
atmosphere" and operated strictly as a business and kept separate from the 
ministry. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to continue to take the lead in running the ministry," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Cerullo said his son David will run the ministry's TV network, which will 
broadcast over the former PTL satellite network. Cerullo has put $7 million 
into escrow to buy the network but is still awaiting approval from the Federal 
Communications Commission. 
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's press conference, Cerullo introduced three men who will help him 
run Heritage USA. One, Bill Lund, worked for Walt Disney in the initial stages 
of developing both Walt Disney World and Epcot Center. Lund is a trustee of 
Occidental College. 
</P>
<P>
Also working with Cerullo will be Hal Tysinger, a North Carolina native who 
specializes in rejuvenating slumping real estate developments, and Dennis 
Kohan, who has more than 25 years experience in financial management. 
</P>
<P>
"Funding for New Heritage USA has been committed by established financial 
institutions here in the United States," said Cerullo, who didn't specify which 
banks. Cerullo has until Nov. 2 to find $45 million needed to finance the theme 
park. 
</P>
<P>
The money will go to pay off the secured creditors owed money by PTL (which 
stands for Praise The Lord). 
</P>
<P>
Alan Elias, a Cerullo spokesman, said a "package of benefits" will also be 
arranged for those who purchased "lifetime partnerships" from PTL while it was 
run by Jim Bakker, now serving a 45-year prison term in Minnesota for fraud and 
conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
Elias also said the buying of Heritage USA is the culmination of two years of 
planning and research into the purchase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
