<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHAT TO SEE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hands-on museums offer children many kinds of learning opportunities. For 
information about hours, fees and special events, call the museums. 
</P>
<P>
Many of the museums have gift shops that sell educational materials, 
exhibit-related toys and games, books and art supplies, and inexpensive items 
for young shoppers. 
</P>
<P>
Children must be accompanied by an adult at all the museums. 
</P>
<P>
Children's Museum of Santa Barbara 
</P>
<P>
* Address: La Cumbre Plaza, 121 S. Hope Ave., Santa Barbara, (805) 682-0845. 
</P>
<P>
* Don't miss: the Painted Cave, Spiral Wishing Well. 
</P>
<P>
Gull Wings 
</P>
<P>
* Address: 418 W. Fourth St., Oxnard, (805) 483-3005. 
</P>
<P>
* Don't miss: the stream table, the tepee and the dinosaur pit. 
</P>
<P>
Kidspace Museum 
</P>
<P>
* Address: 390 S. El Molino Ave., Pasadena, (818) 449-9143 (recording) or (818) 
449-9144. 
</P>
<P>
* Don't miss: the Human Habitrail and Ant Wall. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles Children's Museum 
</P>
<P>
* Address: 310 N. Main St., on the top level of the Los Angeles Mall, Los 
Angeles, (213) 687-8800 (recording) or (213) 687-8801. 
</P>
<P>
* Don't miss: City Streets (see what's under them). 
</P>
