<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY DIGEST: DOWNEY; 
</P>
<P>
DRILLING BEGINS ON NEW WATER WELL -- THE CITY'S 24TH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Drilling began this week on a new municipal water well, located on Paramount 
Boulevard and Gallatin Road. Last month, Downey bought a 2,500-square-foot 
parcel for the well, which is to be a safeguard against breakdowns of existing 
wells. 
</P>
<P>
The well will be 1,000 feet deep, said W.A. Ralph, director of public works. If 
all goes as planned, drilling costs are expected to be $300,000, he said. 
Including the cost of the land, the city is expected to spend $500,000 on the 
new well. The city already has 23 wells, Ralph said. 
</P>
<P>
The city has hired the Anaheim-based consulting firm of Willdan Associates to 
monitor noise levels and environmental impact during the project. 
</P>
<P>
The well is expected to be completed by the end of fall and will pump 3,000 
gallons per minute, Ralph said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
