<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BUS IS THE LATEST ATTRACTION FOR THE FESTIVAL; 
</P>
<P>
TRANSIT: AGENCIES ALLOCATE FUNDS TO IMPROVE SERVICE DURING THE 17-DAY CULTURAL 
EVENT. OFFICIALS HOPE PUBLIC TRANSIT WILL PROVE A CATCHING EXPERIENCE 
YEAR-ROUND. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DIANE HAITHMAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Southern California residents attending September's Los Angeles Festival could 
be in for an exotic new experience: 
</P>
<P>
Riding the bus. 
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Los Angeles County Transportation Commission and the Southern 
California Rapid Transit District approved an allocation of $150,000 to ensure 
that Angelenos can get to the Los Angeles Festival. For many denizens of 
car-crazed L.A., boarding a city bus might represent a bigger culture shock 
than attending a performance by aborigine spiritual dancers or the Kun Opera of 
China. 
</P>
<P>
But festival and transportation officials hope the 750,000 expected to attend 
the 17 days of festival events will help prevent traffic snarls and parking 
hassles at 70 widespread venues by taking public transportation. 
</P>
<P>
They also hope a good experience during the festival will entice passengers to 
commute by bus regularly. 
</P>
<P>
The funds will allow municipal bus lines to extend beyond their usual 
boundaries, beef up the ranks of traffic control officers and engineers and 
provide traffic helicopters. Riders can already get computerized route 
information by calling (800) 2LA-RIDE. 
</P>
<P>
Bill Bicker, Mayor Bradley's transportation adviser, said developing a 
transportation plan for Los Angeles Festival 1990 is more difficult than for 
the 1984 Olympic Arts Festival and the 1987 Los Angeles Festival, where most 
events were by paid attendance. Since 75% of the events at this year's festival 
are free, it's tougher to anticipate attendance, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Bicker said cities will determine which events might be particularly attractive 
to their residents and add bus lines accordingly. "For example, there are some 
ethnic groups (in specific neighborhoods) that might be attracted to particular 
events," Bicker said. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to RTD buses and shuttles, UCLA's Fleet and Transit Service will be 
used to take the public and 500 international artists participating in the 
festival who will be living at UCLA's Artists Village to festival sites. 
</P>
<P>
A shuttle-bus service will be developed with $85,000 of the allocated funds to 
take festivalgoers from parking sites to major festival event areas, some of 
which have little or no parking space. 
</P>
<P>
In some cases, "if you don't utilize the park-and-ride, you don't go to the 
festival," said Errol Talley, special events coordinator for the Department of 
Transportation. 
</P>
<P>
A case in point are the opening-day ceremonies, slated for Sept. 1 at San 
Pedro's Angel's Gate and nearby Point Fermin Park. There are only a few dozen 
parking spaces at the site, but between 60,000 and 100,000 people are expected 
to visit the site over the three-day Labor Day weekend. Signs will direct 
visitors to various large nearby parking sites and shuttles will take them to 
festival site areas. 
</P>
<P>
Bicker said no special transportation or parking will be provided for weekday 
events, which are predicted to draw crowds of less than 1,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES FESTIVAL; FESTIVALS; LOS ANGELES -- TRANSPORTATION; BUSES; 
COMMUTING; ARTS -- LOS ANGELES COUNTY 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
