<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARTIST'S CRITICS TOLD TO PRINT CORRECT VERSION; 
</P>
<P>
PORNOGRAPHY: JUDGE ORDERS A RELIGIOUS GROUP TO DISTRIBUTE AN AMENDED PAMPHLET 
IN NEA BATTLE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A conservative religious group that cropped pictures of an artist's work to 
suggest that it was sexually explicit has been ordered by a federal judge to 
distribute a correction to the pamphlet. 
</P>
<P>
The American Family Assn. of Tupelo, Miss., had reprinted fragments of images 
by David A. Wojnarowicz to promote the organization's contention that the 
National Endowment for the Arts supports pornography. 
</P>
<P>
The ruling Wednesday by U.S. District Judge William C. Conner came in a lawsuit 
by Wojnarowicz. The judge said the pamphlet had probably harmed the artist's 
professional and personal reputation. 
</P>
<P>
Conner barred further publication of the pamphlet, "Your Tax Dollars Helped Pay 
for These Works of Arts." 
</P>
<P>
He also awarded $1 in damages to Wojnarowicz, who had sought up to $1 million. 
He said Wojnarowicz had not proved financial damage because no galleries or 
museums had canceled exhibits of his work. 
</P>
<P>
Conner said the American Family Assn. must send a court-approved correction to 
the 4,000 churches, members of Congress and other individuals who received the 
pamphlet. 
</P>
<P>
The association and its executive director, the Rev. Donald Wildmon, have for 
years led campaigns against films, music, TV shows, magazines and art that they 
deem obscene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
